Dictionary.description: This dictionary contains the values for the propertyClass property of the diggs:Property object and the measurand property of the diggs:Detector object when used within the Test and Monitor DIGGS features. These values serve to define the ultimate results of geotechnical and environmental tests and monitoring activities that result from test procedures and monitoring sensors. The Xpaths to these occurrences are: 1) //diggs:Property/diggs:propertyClass (for Test, MaterialTest or Monitor 2)//diggs:Detector/diggs:measurand (for measurand).
Dictionary.name: DIGGS Measurement Properties

diggs:Definition.description: The gauge gas pressure against the inside of the membrane when the center of the membrane has lifted above its support and moved laterally 0.05-mm (tolerance +0.02, -0.00 mm) into the soil surrounding the blade.
A measure of the resistance of aggregate to surface wear by abrasion.
A relative measure of the resistance of an aggregate to crushing under a gradually applied compressive load.
The percentage by weight of particles whose greatest dimension (length) is 1.8 times their mean dimension.
The percentage by weight of aggregate particles whose least dimension is less than 0.6 times their mean size.
The resistance to impact of aggregates and is measured as percentage of aggregates passing to the total weight of the sample.
The actual measured loss (difference between the original weight and the final weight of the test sample), expressed as a percentage of the original weight of the test sample.
The loss (difference between the original weight and the final weight of the test sample), expressed as an integer.
The actual measured loss (difference between the original weight and the final weight of the test sample), expressed as an integer percentage of the original weight of the test sample.
A measure of the resistance of an aggregate to polishing.

A water content value that gives an idea of strength of aggregate. Aggregates having more water absorption are more porous in nature and are generally considered unsuitable unless they are found to be acceptable based on strength, impact, and hardness tests.
The gauge gas pressure against the inside of the membrane when the center of the membrane has lifted above its support and moved laterally 1.10-mm (60.03 mm) into the soil surrounding the blade.
The volume of clear water in a grout cylinder resulting from grout sedimentation, reported as a percentage of initial total column height.
Total mass (of solids and water) divided by total volume of material, representing natural conditions
The gauge gas pressure against the inside of the membrane when the center of the membrane returns to the A-pressure position during a controlled, gradual deflation following the B-pressure.

California Bearing Ratio is the ratio, expressed as a percentage, of the measured pressure for site soils at a penetration of 0.100 in divided by pressure to achieve equal penetration on a standard soil.

California Bearing Ratio is the ratio, expressed as a percentage, of the measured pressure for site soils at a penetration of 0.200 in divided by pressure to achieve equal penetration on a standard soil.

The Chalk Crushing Value is determined by using the chalk impact crushing test, which measures the rate at which a sample of chalk lumps crushes under impacts from a freefalling rammer. The chalk crushing value can be used, together with the saturation moisture content of the intact chalk lumps, to classify chalk in relation to its behavior as a freshly placed fill material. The test procedure is described for a single sample of chalk lumps, but normal procedure should be to calculate the mean value derived from six such tests on representative samples.
Chloride content by lab testing (corrosivity series)
diggs:Definition.diggs:quantityClass: amount of substance per amount of substance

diggs:Definition.description: represents the total amount of clay sized particles (<2 microns) in a test samples
represents the total amount of clay sized particles (<5 microns) in a test samples
The horizontal coefficient of consolidation as derived from the dissipation test data from a cone penetration or dilatometer test.
The vertical coefficient of consolidation as derived from a one-dimensional consolidation test in the lab.
A coefficient describing the degree of curvature of the grain size distribution. Defined as (d30)^2/((d60)*(d10))
The ratio of horizontal earth pressure to vertical pressure for a sample in the field.
diggs:Definition.identifier: Coefficient of Earth Pressure, In Situ

diggs:Definition.description: The rate at which water flows through a soil is proportional to the hydraulic gradient and is expressed by Darcy's Law. Also known as the hydraulic conductivity. For lab tests, an average of measured values over several permeation trials.
Coefficient of permeability, corrected to 20 degrees C.
Coefficient of permeability, measuring rate of horizontal flow
Coefficient of permeability, measuring rate of vertical flow
The ratio of D60/D10
Shear resistance at zero normal stress ?the portion of the shear strength of a soil indicated by the term c, in Coulomb's equation
Shear resistance at zero normal stress at the residual (or large deformation) strength.
represents the total amount of <1 micron size particles in a test samples

Result from a Consolidation Test. This testis performed to determine the magnitude and rate of void ratio change for a laterally confined soil specimen that is subjected to different vertical pressures. From the measured data, the consolidation curve (pressure-void ratio relationship) can be plotted. This specific value is used for a specific portion of the log vertical pressure - void ratio curve to signify virgin compression. The one-dimension consolidation curve can be used to determine other values (e.g., the recompression index (slope of recompression curve) and the preconsolidation pressure (or maximum past pressure) of the soil).
Result of axial compression test using unconfined compression
A measure of the conductive power of a specified material to the flow of an electric current.

The consistency index (CI) indicates the consistency (firmness) of a soil. It is calculated as CI = (LL-W)/(LL-PL), where W is the existing water content. Soil at the liquid limit will have a consistency index of 0, while soil at the plastic limit will have a consistency index of 100.
Measure of slope of stress-strain curve when specimen is confined. Usually the result from a 1-D consolidation test.
Grain diameter corresponding to 10 percent passing. Intermediate value used to report other results.
Grain diameter corresponding to 30 percent passing. Intermediate value used to report other results.
Grain diameter corresponding to 50 percent passing. Intermediate value used to report other results.
Grain diameter corresponding to 60 percent passing. Intermediate value used to report other results.
Volume of water divided by the volume of voids, expressed as a percentage
The diffrence between the observed friction angle of a soil during dilation and the friction angle at zero dilation
Dilatometer modulus, based on linear elastic theory, and the primary index used in the correlation for the constrained and Young's moduli.

DMT tip bearing (qD) is the axial thrust force at the end of dilatometer blade divided by the projected cross-sectional area of the blade normal to the penetration. The DMT tip bearing is similar to the cone resistance, qc and may be used to evaluate stratigraphy. In cohesionless soils, qD and KD may be used to estimate the friction angle, overconsolidation ratio and at rest coefficient of earth pressure.
Mass of solids divided by total volume

This is a result of a compaction test. It is defined as the maximum dry unit weight that is measured when a specific type and amount of energy is used for the compaction test. This is also the value of the compacted dry unit weight when the soil is at the optimum moisture content.
Vertical effective stress at the center of the membrane before the insertion of the DMT blade.
Volume of filtrate extruded in Pressure Filtration test

Flame Ionization Detector Test detects total concentrations of organic gases and vapors. Gases and vapors are ionized in a flame; a current is produced in proportion to the number of carbon atoms present. Reported result can be in various units of measure, depending upon specific equipment used.
Time for grout specimen to exit flow cone
Angle of friction at constant volume
Measure of frictional resistance of soil. Ratio of shear strength to normal stress.
Angle between the axis of normal stress and the tangent to the Mohr envelope at a point representing the failure-stress condition following large deformation
ratio of sleeve resistance to tip resistance
Test establishes the degree of frost-susceptibility of unbound sub-base and base materials for pavements.
The time it takes for a chemical grout to gel. If determined by rotational viscometer, this is the value where viscosity reaches 100 mpa*s.
Heavy fuel fluorescence detector value measured by sensor

The dimensionless dilatometer horizontal stress index, the primary index used in the correlation for in-situ horizontal stress, overconsolidation ratio, and undrained shear strength in cohesive soils. KD is similar to the at-rest coefficient of earth pressure except that it includes blade penetration effects.
Measured inclination angle (vertical = 0 degrees); bearing unspecified or specified as another property
Inclination measured in defined x direction (specified elsewhere)
Inclination measured in defined y direction (specified elsewhere)
The horizontal component of the original stress status before excavations or other perturbations.
The Point Load Test produces an uncorrected Point Load Test Index (Is), which can be correlated with the uniaxial compressive strength (UCS) of rock.
The Point Load Test produces the Point Load Test Index (Is50), which can be correlated with the uniaxial compressive strength (UCS) of rock.
diggs:Definition.identifier: Size Corrected Point Load Test Index

diggs:Definition.description: Light fuel fluorescence detector value measured by sensor
The oressure at failure during a Pressuremeter test
Coefficient A computed for line loss regression equation Ax^2 + Bx + C
Coefficient B computed for line loss regression equation Ax^2 + Bx + C
Coefficient C computed for line loss regression equation Ax^2 + Bx + C
The correlation coefficient of the line loss regression equation
The liquid limit (LL) is the water content at which a soil changes from plastic to liquid behavior.
Liquid limit determined if sample required oven drying before test

The liquidity index (LI) is used for scaling the natural water content of a soil sample to the limits. It can be calculated as a ratio of difference between natural water content, plastic limit, and liquid limit: LI=(W-PL)/(LL-PL) where W is the natural water content.
The amount of organic matter in a soil that derives from peat, organic muck, plant material such as wood, roots, grass, or carbonaceous maTerials such as lignite, coal, etc.
A unit devised to quantify the water permeability of bedrock and the hydraulic conductivity resulting from fractures.
Time for grout speciment to exit marsh funnel
Dimensionless dilatometer material index, used to identify soil type and delineate stratigraphy.

The Moisture Condition Value (MCV) is determined from a moisture condition test, a physical test indicating how much compactive effort is needed to compact a sample of soil at a particular moisture content.
Shear modulus, denoted by G, is defined as the ratio of shear stress to the shear strain.

The tangent modulus of the initial, linear portion of a stress-strain curve for material in axial compression or tension is called Young's modulus, also known as the tensile (compression) modulus. It is defined as the ratio of the uniaxial stress over the uniaxial strain in the range of stress in which Hooke' Law holds. It is often calculated using theory of elasticity from other tests.
Grout or mud density determined using a mud balance
Value from Standard Penetration Test (SPT) to define advancement in terms of blows required to drive a specific sampler I foot into the soil using a hammer that provides a specific impact energy.

Calculated value that corrects the value of the Standard Penetration Blow Count (N), to account for energy of the hammer (specifically normalized to 60% energy) and specific overburden conditions (specifically to an overburden stress of 1 ton per square foot).
Calculated value that corrects the value of the Standard Penetration Blow Count (N-value), to account for energy of the hammer (specifically normalized to 60% energy).

A value of true for this property indiates that no plastic limit can be . In such cases the value of the plastic limit should be left empty or set to the null value, and the value of non_plastic set to true.

A calculation that reflects the maximum past consolidation test that the in situ soil has been subjected to compared to the current vertical overburden stress on the sample in the field. This value is usually measured from the one-dimensional consolidation tests. Often referenced as the parameter to track the stress history.

A-Reading corrected for the DA membrane stiffness at 0.05 mm expansion, the 0.05 mm expansion itself and the gauge pressure deviation from zero. This corrected pressure is referred to as p0. This is an intermediate result from a flat plate dilatometer test.

B-Reading corrected for the DB membrane stiffness at 1.10 mm expansion and the gauge pressure deviation from zero. This corrected pressure is referred to as p1. This is an intermediate result from a flat plate dilatometer test.

C-Reading corrected for the DA membrane stiffness at 0.05 mm expansion and the gauge pressure deviation from zero. This corrected pressure is referred to as p2. This is an intermediate result from a flat plate dilatometer test.
The percentage of particles that pass through the #200 sieve (<0.075-mm).
The percentage of particles that are retained on the #4 and larger sizes (>4.75 mm).
The percentage of particles thatpass the #4 sivve and are retained on the #200 sieve (<4.75 mm and >0.075-mm).
A meassure of how acidic or basic a soil or water is.
Measures volatile organic compounds and other gases, expressed in parts per million.
The plastic limit (PL) is the water content where soil transitions between brittle and plastic behavior.

The plasticity index (PI) is a measure of the plasticity of a soil. The plasticity index is a measure of the range of water contents where the soil exhibits plastic properties. The PI is the difference between the liquid limit and the plastic limit (PI = LL-PL). (Soils with a high PI tend to be clay, those with a lower PI tend to be silt, and those with a PI of 0 (non-plastic) tend to have little or no silt or clay.)
The Point Load Test produces the Point Load Test Index (Is50), which can be correlated with the uniaxial compressive strength (UCS) of rock.
Ratio of the transverse contraction of a body to its longitudinal extension when stretched. Typical values in minerals are from 0.15 to 0.3 (Carbonates:0.15, Sandstones:0.2, Shales:0.25).
the value of pore pressure measured in the field after dissipation of induced excess pore pressure. Could also be from CPTu test
The pore-water pressure acting at the center of the membrane before the insertion of the DMT blade (often assumed as hydrostatic below the water table surface).
Measured pore pressure from u1 transducer on tip.
Measured pore pressure from u2 transducer behind tip.
Measured pore pressure from u3 transducer behind sleeve.

Result from a Consolidation Test. This test is performed to determine the magnitude and rate of void ratio change for a laterally confined soil specimen that is subjected to different vertical pressures. From the measured data, the consolidation curve (pressure-void ratio relationship) can be plotted. This specific value is used for a specific portion of the log vertical pressure - void ratio curve to signify the largest value of stress that sample has experienced before the performance of this test. It is a calculation results usually obtained by a construction technique using laboratory test results.
Value derived from a pressure filtration test

Result from a Consolidation Test. This test is performed to determine the magnitude and rate of void ratio change for a laterally confined soil specimen that is subjected to different vertical pressures. From the measured data, the consolidation curve (pressure-void ratio relationship) can be plotted. This specific value is used for a specific portion of the log vertical pressure - void ratio curve to signify a response due to the unloading and reloading of a sample that is on the virgin curve.
A 'measure of the ability of chemical/biochemical systems to oxidize (lose electrons) or reduce (gain electrons).
The density of a granular specimen relative to its maximum and minimum density (or void ratio)
A measure of the resisting power of a specified material to the flow of an electric current.
The open space in a rock divided by the total rock volume.

The Schmidt Hardness Test utilizes a hammer mass launched against an impact plunger. The amount of hammer mass rebound depends on the hardness of the test piece. This rebound amount is then shown on a scale of 10 to 100.
the ratio of the strength of the soil in the undisturbed state to that of the soil in the remolded state.
Setting time for grout

The peak shear resistance of an intact specimen when pore fluid pressures, generated during the course of shearing the soil, are able to dissipate during shearing. It also applies where no pore water exists in the soil (the soil is dry) and hence pore fluid pressures are negligible.

The peak shear strength of an intact specimen when no volume change is allowed during the tests. The value can be measured in the lab and in the field. In both cases, the value can be calculated from different tests.
A measure of the shear strength of the soil for which the shear stress remains essentially constant with increasing shear displacement andwhen no volume change is allowed during the tests.

The height of the rebound travel of the Scleroscope hammer is measured on a graduated scale. The scale of the rebound is arbitrarily chosen and consists on Shore units, divided into 100 parts, which represent the average rebound from pure hardened high-carbon steel. The scale is continued higher than 100 to include metals having greater hardness.
The amount of grout shrinkage, reported as a percentage of total volume
The shrinkage limit (SL) is the water content below which a soil undergoes no further volume change.
The ratio of a given volume change expressed as a percentage of the dry volume to the corresponding change in water content above the shrinkage limit.

The Slake Durability Index predicts the long-term durability of the rock specimens, to establish weathering and degradation characteristics of each rock type, and to assess the impact of water on the rock degradation.
Value of stress measured on sleeve of cone during penetration
Amount of slump of grout sample
Soil moisture content measured by sensor (eg CPT)
Soil suction value
A value derived from a dilatometer test, using the dilatometer modulus and material index.

The apparent specific gravity is designated Ga and is the ratio of the weight in air of a unit volume of the impermeable portion of aggregate to the weight in air of an equal volume of distilled water, both at a stated temperature. The impermeable portion of a porous material, such as most large soil grains, includes the solid material plus impermeable pores or voids within the particles.

The bulk specific gravity is designated Gm and is the ratio of the weight in air of a unit volume of aggregate (including permeable and impermeable voids in the particles, but not the voids between the particles) to the weight of an equal volume of distilled water at a stated temperature.

The specific gravity of solids (Gs) is the bulk density of the solid particles relative to the density of water. It is a required parameter to assess void ratio. Its value is a function of the mineralogy of the solid particles. It is commonly assumed by geotechnical engineers.
Sulfate content by lab testing (corrosivity series)
diggs:Definition.diggs:quantityClass: amount of substance per amount of substance

diggs:Definition.description: Thec ontraction of a gel accompanied by the separating out of liquid. It is calculated as a percent of volume or mass loss.

The syneresis value of a gel specimen divided by its surface area; accounts for variability in syneresis of a gel depending on the amount of the gel exposed to air. Calculated as mass loss divided by surface area
Time until pore pressure reaches the halfway pressure (u50) between starting dynamic pore pressure and equilibrium pore pressure
Measured temperature
A measure of the resistance of aggregate crushing.
Thrust force required to advance the dilatometer to the test depth. This force is exclusive of soil or other friction along the push rods. This thrust is referred to as qd.
Time of measurement
A measure of stress measured at tip of cone during penetration
Tip resistance corrected for u2 pore pressure measurement
Pore pressure midway between dynamic pore pressure and equilibrium pore pressure
Unit weight of a soil mass is the ratio of the total weight of soil to the total volume of soil.
The two-letter symbol of soil type of the Unified Soil Classification System, used in engineering and geology to describe the texture and grain size of a soil.
The two letter symbol of soil type of the Unified Soil Classification System of material passing 425 micron screen
diggs:Definition.identifier: USCS Classification of Material Passing 425 Screen

diggs:Definition.description: Total vertical stress at the center of the membrane before the insertion of the DMT blade, generally calculated from unit weights estimated using the DMT results.
The decrease in volume of a soil mass when the water content is reduced from a given percentage to the shrinkage limit and which is expressed as percentage of dry volume of the soil mass.
Descriptive result of a washout test

Also referred to as moisture content, this is the mass of water divided by the mass of the solids, expressed as a percentage. Use of this parameter is for natural conditions. Determined in a laboratory or via sensor.

This is a result of a compaction test. It is defined as the moisture content at the maximum dry unit weight as measured when a specific type and amount of energy is used for the compaction test. This is also the value of the compaction moisture content when the soils achieves the maximum dry unit weight.
Measured depth to water below datum, typically directly observed or computed from a pressure transducer
Measured elevation of water level, typically directly observed or computed from a pressure transducer
Depth to water calculated from measured equilibrium pore pressure
Water elevation calculated from measured equilibrium pore pressure
Estimate of water depth from insitu measurement (eg CPT, DMT)
Estimate of water elevation from insitu measurement (eg CPT, DMT)
